{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Use British English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox academic | name = Gianni De Farja | image = | birth_name = Gianni De Farja | birth_place = [[Bologna]], [[Italy]] | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|04|09|df=yes}} | occupation = Economics professor | workplaces = [[University of Nottingham]], England }}
'''Gianni De Fraja''' is a Professor of Economics at the [[University of Nottingham]], [[England]] and a Research Fellow (CEPR).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cepr.org/default_static.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-03-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060302222021/http://www.cepr.org/default_static.htm |archivedate=2 March 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
He was born in [[Bologna]], where he spent the first five years of his life, before moving to [[Bassano del Grappa]] and then on to [[Mestre]], near [[Venice]], where he lived until he was eighteen. He attended [[SSSUP]] college in [[Pisa]] from which he graduated in 1982. He then moved to a house near the [[Chianti Hills]] near [[Vagliagli]] where he took his [[doctorate]] at [[Siena]] with a thesis on [[Game Theory]].
After a year in Siena he was encouraged by his teachers to go abroad and so went to [[England]], to [[Linacre College, Oxford]]. After two years in Oxford he returned to [[Italy]] for [[military service]] in the [[Italian Army]]. After a year he returned to complete his [[thesis]] on oligopolistic competition.
Since finishing his studies in Oxford he has taken up [[academic]] positions in the universities of [[University of Leicester|Leicester]], [[University of Bristol|Bristol]] and [[University of York|York]]. He has also been on academic trips to [[Tokyo]], [[Bonn]] and [[Barcelona]]. After thirteen years in York, he is now settled in Leicester, with two daughters and a son.
Between 1999 and 2005, he was Managing Editor of the ''[[Bulletin of Economic Research]]''. His research interests are in the areas of [[Public economics]], [[Economics of education]], [[Regulation]], and [[Game Theory]]. He has published papers in, among others, ''[[Journal of Public Economics]]'', ''[[International Economic Review]]'', ''[[Review of Economic Studies]]'', ''[[Economic Journal]]'', ''[[Journal of Political Economy]]'', and ''Oxford Economic Papers''. As posted on his personal webpage [https://web.archive.org/web/20051201121128/http://www.le.ac.uk/economics/gdf4/], he considers himself a [[Bright (movement)|bright]].
He has been elected head of the Department of Economics at the University of Leicester and will begin his mandate in September 2008. In 2011 he was replaced as head of department by Stephen Hall.
